# Ruby Best Practices
# Comprehensive Ruby Best Practices

This guide provides comprehensive best practices for Ruby development, focusing on code organization, performance, security, and maintainability.

## Modern Ruby 3.4+ Best Practices

### Use `it` for Simple Block Operations (Ruby 3.4+)
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use `it` for simple, clear block operations
users.map { it.name }
articles.select { it.published? }
numbers.filter { it.positive? }

# ❌ DON'T: Use `it` when logic is complex or unclear
users.map { |user| "#{user.first_name} #{user.last_name}" }  # explicit parameter is clearer

# ❌ DON'T: Mix `it` with numbered parameters
users.map { _1.name + it.email }  # SyntaxError
```

### Leverage YJIT for Production Performance (Ruby 3.1+)
```ruby
# Enable YJIT in production for 5-7% performance boost
# Add to your deployment configuration:
# RUBY_YJIT_ENABLE=1

# Monitor YJIT performance:
if defined?(RubyVM::YJIT.enabled?) && RubyVM::YJIT.enabled?
  stats = RubyVM::YJIT.runtime_stats
  Rails.logger.info "YJIT compilation ratio: #{stats[:compiled_method_calls] / stats[:total_method_calls].to_f * 100}%"
end
```

### Optimize JSON Performance (Ruby 3.4+)
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Take advantage of 1.5x faster JSON.parse in Ruby 3.4
# Especially beneficial for API-heavy applications
parsed_data = JSON.parse(response_body)

# ✅ DO: Consider using Oj for even better performance in critical paths
require 'oj'
parsed_data = Oj.load(response_body, mode: :compat)
```

## Ruby Fundamentals

### Prefer Explicit Over Implicit
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Be explicit about intentions
def process_user(user, send_email: false, update_profile: true)
  # Clear what the method does
end

# ❌ DON'T: Use implicit behavior
def process_user(user, options = {})
  # Unclear what options are available
end
```

### Use Safe Navigation Operator
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use safe navigation to prevent NoMethodError
user&.profile&.avatar&.url

# ✅ DO: Combine with other operators when appropriate
user&.posts&.any? { |post| post.published? }

# ❌ DON'T: Use when nil is not expected
current_user&.id  # If current_user should never be nil
```

### Master String Interpolation
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use string interpolation over concatenation
"Hello, #{user.name}!"

# ✅ DO: Use proper formatting for complex data
"User #{user.id} has #{user.posts.count} #{'post'.pluralize(user.posts.count)}"

# ❌ DON'T: Use concatenation for dynamic strings
"Hello, " + user.name + "!"
```

## Object-Oriented Design

### Follow Single Responsibility Principle
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Each class has one clear purpose
class UserEmailValidator
  def initialize(user)
    @user = user
  end

  def valid?
    return false if @user.email.blank?
    return false unless email_format_valid?
    return false if email_taken?
    true
  end

  private

  def email_format_valid?
    @user.email.match?(/\A[\w+\-.]+@[a-z\d\-]+(\.[a-z\d\-]+)*\.[a-z]+\z/i)
  end

  def email_taken?
    User.exists?(email: @user.email)
  end
end

# ❌ DON'T: Classes that do too many things
class UserManager  # Validates, sends emails, updates profiles, etc.
end
```

### Use Modules for Shared Behavior
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Extract common behavior into modules
module Timestampable
  extend ActiveSupport::Concern

  included do
    scope :recent, -> { where(created_at: 1.week.ago..) }
    scope :older_than, ->(date) { where(created_at: ..date) }
  end

  def age_in_days
    (Time.current - created_at) / 1.day
  end
end

class Post < ApplicationRecord
  include Timestampable
end

class Comment < ApplicationRecord
  include Timestampable
end
```

### Prefer Composition Over Inheritance
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use composition for flexible behavior
class PaymentProcessor
  def initialize(gateway: StripeGateway.new, logger: Rails.logger)
    @gateway = gateway
    @logger = logger
  end

  def process(payment)
    @logger.info "Processing payment #{payment.id}"
    @gateway.charge(payment)
  end
end

# ❌ DON'T: Deep inheritance hierarchies
class StripePaymentProcessor < PaymentProcessor < BaseProcessor < ApplicationService
end
```

## Error Handling and Exceptions

### Use Specific Exception Types
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Create specific exception classes
class PaymentFailedError < StandardError
  attr_reader :payment_id, :gateway_error

  def initialize(payment_id, gateway_error)
    @payment_id = payment_id
    @gateway_error = gateway_error
    super("Payment #{payment_id} failed: #{gateway_error}")
  end
end

# ✅ DO: Rescue specific exceptions
begin
  process_payment(payment)
rescue PaymentFailedError => e
  logger.error "Payment processing failed: #{e.gateway_error}"
  redirect_to payment_failed_path
rescue ActiveRecord::RecordInvalid => e
  logger.error "Invalid payment record: #{e.record.errors.full_messages}"
  redirect_to new_payment_path
end
```

### Handle Errors Gracefully
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Provide meaningful error messages and recovery options
class UserService
  def create_user(params)
    user = User.new(params)

    if user.save
      Result.success(user)
    else
      Result.failure(user.errors.full_messages)
    end
  rescue ActiveRecord::RecordNotUnique
    Result.failure(["Email address is already taken"])
  end

  private

  Result = Struct.new(:success?, :data, :errors) do
    def self.success(data)
      new(true, data, nil)
    end

    def self.failure(errors)
      new(false, nil, errors)
    end
  end
end
```

## Performance Optimization

### Use Appropriate Data Structures
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use Set for membership tests
ALLOWED_ROLES = Set.new(%w[admin editor viewer]).freeze

def authorized?(role)
  ALLOWED_ROLES.include?(role)
end

# ✅ DO: Use Hash for key-value lookups
STATUS_MESSAGES = {
  pending: "Your request is being processed",
  approved: "Your request has been approved",
  rejected: "Your request has been rejected"
}.freeze

# ❌ DON'T: Use Array for frequent lookups
ALLOWED_ROLES = %w[admin editor viewer]  # O(n) lookup time
```

### Optimize Database Queries
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use includes to prevent N+1 queries
posts = Post.includes(:author, :comments).limit(10)

# ✅ DO: Use select to load only needed columns
users = User.select(:id, :name, :email).where(active: true)

# ✅ DO: Use find_each for large datasets
User.find_each(batch_size: 1000) do |user|
  UserMailer.newsletter(user).deliver_later
end

# ❌ DON'T: Load unnecessary data
posts = Post.all  # Loads all columns and all records
posts.each { |post| puts post.title }  # Only needed title
```

### Memory Management
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use symbols for static strings and identifiers
user.update(status: :active)

# ✅ DO: Use frozen strings for constants
DEFAULT_MESSAGE = "Welcome to our platform!".freeze

# ✅ DO: Clear large objects when done
def process_large_file(file_path)
  data = File.read(file_path)  # Large data
  result = transform_data(data)
  data = nil  # Clear reference to help GC
  result
end
```

## Security Best Practices

### Validate and Sanitize Input
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use strong parameters in Rails
def user_params
  params.require(:user).permit(:name, :email, :age)
end

# ✅ DO: Validate data at multiple levels
class User < ApplicationRecord
  validates :email, presence: true, format: { with: URI::MailTo::EMAIL_REGEXP }
  validates :age, numericality: { greater_than: 0, less_than: 150 }

  before_save :normalize_email

  private

  def normalize_email
    self.email = email.downcase.strip
  end
end
```

### Protect Against Common Vulnerabilities
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use secure random for tokens
class User < ApplicationRecord
  before_create :generate_auth_token

  private

  def generate_auth_token
    self.auth_token = SecureRandom.urlsafe_base64(32)
  end
end

# ✅ DO: Sanitize HTML output
def safe_user_content(content)
  ActionController::Base.helpers.sanitize(content)
end

# ✅ DO: Use constant-time comparison for secrets
def valid_token?(provided_token)
  ActiveSupport::SecurityUtils.secure_compare(
    provided_token.to_s,
    stored_token.to_s
  )
end
```

## Testing Best Practices

### Write Clear and Focused Tests
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use descriptive test names
RSpec.describe UserService do
  describe "#create_user" do
    context "when given valid parameters" do
      it "creates a new user and returns success result" do
        params = { name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com" }

        result = UserService.create_user(params)

        expect(result.success?).to be true
        expect(result.data).to be_a(User)
        expect(result.data.name).to eq("John Doe")
      end
    end

    context "when given invalid parameters" do
      it "returns failure result with error messages" do
        params = { name: "", email: "invalid-email" }

        result = UserService.create_user(params)

        expect(result.success?).to be false
        expect(result.errors).to include("Name can't be blank")
      end
    end
  end
end
```

### Use Test Doubles Appropriately
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Mock external dependencies
RSpec.describe PaymentService do
  let(:gateway) { instance_double(StripeGateway) }
  let(:service) { PaymentService.new(gateway: gateway) }

  it "processes payment through gateway" do
    payment = build(:payment, amount: 100)
    allow(gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return(success: true)

    result = service.process(payment)

    expect(gateway).to have_received(:charge).with(payment)
    expect(result.success?).to be true
  end
end

# ❌ DON'T: Mock everything
it "calculates total" do
  user = instance_double(User)
  order = instance_double(Order)
  # Too much mocking makes test brittle and unclear
end
```

