### Use Appropriate Comments
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Explain why, not what
class PriceCalculator
  # Calculate price including dynamic pricing based on demand and inventory levels
  # This uses a complex algorithm that factors in:
  # - Current inventory levels
  # - Historical demand patterns
  # - Seasonal adjustments
  def calculate_dynamic_price(product)
    base_price = product.base_price
    demand_multiplier = calculate_demand_multiplier(product)
    inventory_adjustment = calculate_inventory_adjustment(product)

    base_price * demand_multiplier * inventory_adjustment
  end

  # ❌ DON'T: Explain obvious code
  # This method calculates the product price
  def calculate_price(product)
    product.base_price * 1.1  # Add 10% markup
  end
end
```

## Advanced Ruby Techniques

### Use Metaprogramming Judiciously
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use metaprogramming to reduce repetition when it adds clarity
class Configuration
  SETTINGS = %w[database_url redis_url secret_key].freeze

  SETTINGS.each do |setting|
    define_method(setting) do
      ENV[setting.upcase]
    end

    define_method("#{setting}=") do |value|
      ENV[setting.upcase] = value
    end
  end
end

# ❌ DON'T: Use metaprogramming when simple methods are clearer
class User
  %w[name email].each do |attr|
    define_method("formatted_#{attr}") do
      send(attr).titleize
    end
  end
end

# Simpler and clearer:
class User
  def formatted_name
    name.titleize
  end

  def formatted_email
    email.titleize
  end
end
```

### Leverage Enumerable Methods
```ruby
# ✅ DO: Use appropriate enumerable methods
# Transform data
user_names = users.map(&:name)
active_users = users.select(&:active?)
user_lookup = users.index_by(&:id)

# Aggregate data
total_age = users.sum(&:age)
average_age = users.sum(&:age) / users.count.to_f
oldest_user = users.max_by(&:age)

# Check conditions
any_admin = users.any?(&:admin?)
all_verified = users.all?(&:verified?)

# ✅ DO: Chain methods for complex transformations
result = users
  .select(&:active?)
  .group_by(&:department)
  .transform_values { |dept_users| dept_users.sum(&:salary) }

# ❌ DON'T: Use loops when enumerable methods are more expressive
total = 0
users.each { |user| total += user.age }  # Use sum instead
```

